{"summary":"Several studies have looked at the effects of thinning trees on butterfly and moth populations. Four studies in Finland and the USA discovered that thinning coniferous woodland, in some cases with additional management like mulching or prescribed burning, led to a higher abundance and species richness of butterflies (3940). Another study in the Czech Republic showed that forest plots that had been partially cleared had a higher species richness of butterflies, but a lower species richness of moths, than closed-canopy forests (3940). One study in Côte d’Ivoire, however, found that a thinned forest had a similar abundance and diversity of fruit-feeding butterflies as a naturally regenerating, unmanaged forest, but that rarer species were caught less often in the thinned forest (3940).

Studies have also examined the effects of different logging methods on butterfly and moth populations. A study in Brazil discovered that a forest that was managed with reduced-impact logging had a greater abundance of butterflies than a primary forest, as well as a similar diversity and species richness (3867). Another study in Brazil found that fruit-feeding butterflies were most abundant in forests with an intermediate intensity of reduced-impact logging (3867). In contrast, a study in the USA reported that forests where single tree selection harvesting was used had a lower species richness of moths than forests that were unharvested (3867).

